circumstances.circumstancesOfRecovery: Victim was an unidentified homicide victim of 1979, Tuscaloosa, Alabama.  Determined to be a homicide and probable sexual assault.  Believed to be from the Jefferson County, Alabama area, possibly Bessemer AL.  Also could have been a hitch hiker or prostitute.  A suspect from Bessemer, AL was convicted of killing two other women and discarding their bodies in the same general area, but this individual victim was never identified.  Of the two identified victims, both were determined to have been last seen in the Bessemer, AL area.   One identified victim was a hitchhiker, not a resident of Bessemer. This victim was never identified despite extensive investigation and media coverage in 1979, leading to belief that she may have also been a hitchhiker or prostitute from another area.

circumstances.circumstancesOfRecovery: Incomplete skeletal remains were discovered by three engineers who were surveying a sloped wooded property in a commercial/industrial area.  The remains were found to be contained within a long sleeve shirt and pants.  A Lloyd Nolan Hospital Ident-A-Band bracelet manufactured by Hollister, Inc. was found with the remains. It was determined that the bracelet was manufactured between 1966-1984 and was issued by Lloyd Nolan Hospital to a 40 year old black male.  Lloyd Nolan Hospital has since closed in 2004 and was subsequently torn down in 2009.  All attempts to identify the patient issued the bracelet failed.
